  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The 2022 study titled \"Uncovering circuit mechanisms of current sinks and sources with biophysical simulations of primary visual cortex,\" first released as a preprint on bioRxiv, has garnered notable academic attention, as evidenced by its 50 citations and proven downstream reuse in 51 subsequent works. This research engages key institutions such as the Allen Institute and contributes to advancing our understanding of visual cortex circuitry.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Initially shared as a preprint on bioRxiv, this research has successfully transitioned to a peer-reviewed publication, reflecting a rigorous validation of its findings. The combined impact of both versions is illustrated by 50 total citations, with 46 specifically attributed to the published version in the journal eLife. This indicates the work's significant contribution to the field of neuroscience, particularly in understanding the biophysical mechanisms that underlie visual processing.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The study has influenced a diverse array of subsequent research, as highlighted by its proven downstream reuse in 51 different contexts. This extensive engagement underscores not only the relevance of the research findings but also the importance of open data practices. The accompanying dataset hosted on Dryad further emphasizes a commitment to data accessibility, facilitating further exploration and validation by the scientific community.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The work has found a receptive audience across leading scientific venues, particularly within the United States and Norway, highlighting a geographic footprint that reflects institutional backing from prominent organizations, including the Allen Institute and the University of Oslo. The mixture of citations from reputable journals such as Nature Neuroscience and The Journal of Physiology evidences a wide-reaching impact among researchers focused on system neuroscience.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Moreover, the study plays an essential role in the discourse of current biophysical simulation methodologies. By addressing complex mechanisms in the primary visual cortex, it contributes to ongoing debates and reviews in the field, establishing itself as a key reference point for future investigations into neural circuitry. This work exemplifies the synergy between foundational research outputs and the evolving landscape of neuroscience inquiry.</p>",
